1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,566
Right now, the phone in your pocket is

2
00:00:02,789 --> 00:00:05,354
keeping a record of where you are. It

3
00:00:05,577 --> 00:00:08,143
does it automatically, every few minutes, and it

4
00:00:08,366 --> 00:00:10,932
sends that record to your carrier. In

5
00:00:11,155 --> 00:00:13,721
2011, police used 127 days of one man's

6
00:00:13,944 --> 00:00:16,509
location records to place him near a string

7
00:00:16,732 --> 00:00:19,298
of robberies — and they got those records

8
00:00:19,521 --> 00:00:22,087
without a warrant. The question that reached

9
00:00:22,310 --> 00:00:24,876
the Supreme Court was simple and enormous: when

10
00:00:25,099 --> 00:00:27,664
your phone tracks you, who does that trail

11
00:00:27,887 --> 00:00:30,453
belong to?

12
00:00:31,077 --> 00:00:33,876
We have spent two episodes watching the Court

13
00:00:34,119 --> 00:00:36,919
draw the line of privacy — first on

14
00:00:37,162 --> 00:00:39,961
a public sidewalk, then on the phone in

15
00:00:40,205 --> 00:00:43,004
your pocket. Each time, the rule depended on

16
00:00:43,247 --> 00:00:46,047
something you could point to: a body, a

17
00:00:46,290 --> 00:00:49,089
device, an expectation you could see. But your

18
00:00:49,333 --> 00:00:52,132
phone broke that logic. It exposes you constantly,

19
00:00:52,375 --> 00:00:55,174
not because you chose to, but because that

20
00:00:55,418 --> 00:00:58,217
is how the network works. Over the

21
00:00:58,460 --> 00:01:01,260
next twelve minutes: the case that asked whether

22
00:01:01,503 --> 00:01:04,302
decades of old privacy rules could survive a

23
00:01:04,546 --> 00:01:07,345
device that follows you everywhere, and the line

24
00:01:07,588 --> 00:01:10,388
the Court finally drew in the digital age.

25
00:01:11,032 --> 00:01:13,952
In 2010 and 2011, a series of armed

26
00:01:14,206 --> 00:01:17,127
robberies hit stores around Detroit, Michigan — electronics

27
00:01:17,381 --> 00:01:20,302
shops and phone stores, hit by a rotating

28
00:01:20,556 --> 00:01:23,476
crew. When the police arrested a suspect,

29
00:01:23,730 --> 00:01:26,651
he confessed and gave them names and, crucially,

30
00:01:26,905 --> 00:01:29,826
phone numbers of the men he said were

31
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:33,001
involved.

32
00:01:33,655 --> 00:01:35,416
One of those numbers belonged to a man

33
00:01:35,569 --> 00:01:37,330
named Timothy Carpenter.

34
00:01:37,884 --> 00:01:40,565
To build their case, investigators did not need

35
00:01:40,798 --> 00:01:43,478
to follow Carpenter or watch his house. They

36
00:01:43,711 --> 00:01:46,392
went to his wireless carriers and asked for

37
00:01:46,625 --> 00:01:49,305
something most people in 2011 did not know

38
00:01:49,538 --> 00:01:52,219
existed: his cell-site location information.

39
00:01:52,852 --> 00:01:55,380
Here is what that is. Every time your

40
00:01:55,599 --> 00:01:58,126
phone connects to a tower — to send

41
00:01:58,346 --> 00:02:00,873
a text, take a call, or just check

42
00:02:01,093 --> 00:02:03,620
for messages in the background — the network

43
00:02:03,840 --> 00:02:06,367
logs which tower it used. Those towers

44
00:02:06,587 --> 00:02:09,114
cover known areas. String the records together over

45
00:02:09,334 --> 00:02:11,861
days and weeks, and you do not just

46
00:02:12,081 --> 00:02:14,608
get a few points. You get a map

47
00:02:14,828 --> 00:02:17,355
of a person's movements, hour by hour.

48
00:02:17,975 --> 00:02:21,505
The government obtained around 127 days of Carpenter's

49
00:02:21,812 --> 00:02:25,341
records — almost 13,000 location points, about 12,898

50
00:02:25,648 --> 00:02:29,178
in all, tracing where his phone had been

51
00:02:29,485 --> 00:02:33,015
The data placed him near several of

52
00:02:33,322 --> 00:02:36,851
the robberies when they happened. He was convicted

53
00:02:37,158 --> 00:02:40,688
and sentenced to 116 years in prison.

54
00:02:41,395 --> 00:02:43,655
And the police had gathered that 127-day map

55
00:02:43,852 --> 00:02:46,111
without a warrant. They had not convinced

56
00:02:46,308 --> 00:02:48,568
a judge that there was probable cause. They

57
00:02:48,764 --> 00:02:51,024
had used a federal law that let them

58
00:02:51,220 --> 00:02:53,480
get the records on a much weaker showing

59
00:02:53,676 --> 00:02:55,936
— a standard far below the one the

60
00:02:56,133 --> 00:02:58,392
Fourth Amendment usually demands. The reason they

61
00:02:58,589 --> 00:03:00,848
were allowed to do that came from a

62
00:03:01,045 --> 00:03:03,305
rule almost no one outside a courtroom had

63
00:03:03,501 --> 00:03:05,761
ever heard of.

64
00:03:06,358 --> 00:03:09,317
That rule is called the third-party doctrine, and

65
00:03:09,574 --> 00:03:12,533
to understand Carpenter, you have to understand it.

66
00:03:13,191 --> 00:03:15,705
In the 1970s, the Supreme Court decided a

67
00:03:15,924 --> 00:03:18,438
pair of cases about information people had handed

68
00:03:18,657 --> 00:03:21,171
to someone else — bank records in one,

69
00:03:21,389 --> 00:03:23,903
the phone numbers a person dialed in another

70
00:03:24,122 --> 00:03:26,636
The Court's logic was that once you

71
00:03:26,854 --> 00:03:29,368
voluntarily give information to a third party —

72
00:03:29,587 --> 00:03:32,101
a bank, a phone company — you have

73
00:03:32,320 --> 00:03:34,834
given up your reasonable expectation of privacy in

74
00:03:35,052 --> 00:03:37,566
it. You took the risk that they might

75
00:03:37,785 --> 00:03:40,299
turn it over.

76
00:03:40,918 --> 00:03:43,776
Remember the principle from our last episodes: privacy

77
00:03:44,025 --> 00:03:46,883
is protected when society accepts your expectation as

78
00:03:47,131 --> 00:03:49,989
reasonable. The third-party doctrine said that if you

79
00:03:50,237 --> 00:03:53,095
shared the information, that expectation was gone. The

80
00:03:53,344 --> 00:03:56,202
government could get it without a warrant, because,

81
00:03:56,450 --> 00:03:59,308
in the eyes of the law, it was

82
00:03:59,556 --> 00:04:02,414
no longer really yours.

83
00:04:03,063 --> 00:04:05,439
In 1979, applied to a list of dialed

84
00:04:05,646 --> 00:04:08,022
phone numbers, that idea was already aggressive, but

85
00:04:08,228 --> 00:04:10,604
it was containable. A list of numbers

86
00:04:10,810 --> 00:04:13,186
is thin. It does not tell you where

87
00:04:13,393 --> 00:04:15,769
a person slept, who they visited, or whether

88
00:04:15,975 --> 00:04:18,351
they went to a clinic, a church, or

89
00:04:18,558 --> 00:04:20,933
a protest.

90
00:04:21,541 --> 00:04:23,955
Cell-site records are different in kind, not just

91
00:04:24,165 --> 00:04:26,579
degree. You do not choose to send

92
00:04:26,789 --> 00:04:29,204
them. Simply by carrying a phone that is

93
00:04:29,414 --> 00:04:31,828
turned on — which, in modern life, is

94
00:04:32,038 --> 00:04:34,453
nearly everyone, nearly always — you generate a

95
00:04:34,663 --> 00:04:37,077
continuous record of your location and hand it

96
00:04:37,287 --> 00:04:39,701
to a company. There is no door

97
00:04:39,911 --> 00:04:42,326
to close. There is no way to step

98
00:04:42,536 --> 00:04:44,950
out of the booth. To opt out of

99
00:04:45,160 --> 00:04:47,575
the tracking, you would have to disconnect from

100
00:04:47,785 --> 00:04:50,199
modern life entirely.

101
00:04:50,810 --> 00:04:53,451
And there is no realistic way out. You

102
00:04:53,681 --> 00:04:56,322
cannot hold a job, raise a family, or

103
00:04:56,551 --> 00:04:59,193
call for help in modern life without a

104
00:04:59,422 --> 00:05:02,064
phone, and the moment it is on, the

105
00:05:02,293 --> 00:05:04,934
tracking begins. The 1970s idea of voluntarily sharing

106
00:05:05,164 --> 00:05:07,805
assumed a choice. Carrying a phone is not

107
00:05:08,035 --> 00:05:10,676
a choice in that sense — it is

108
00:05:10,906 --> 00:05:13,547
the price of admission to ordinary life.

109
00:05:14,177 --> 00:05:16,929
So Carpenter's case forced a collision. On one

110
00:05:17,168 --> 00:05:19,919
side stood a 1970s rule: share it, and

111
00:05:20,158 --> 00:05:22,910
you lose it. On the other stood a

112
00:05:23,149 --> 00:05:25,900
device that shares your location constantly, automatically, with

113
00:05:26,140 --> 00:05:28,891
no real choice involved. If the old

114
00:05:29,130 --> 00:05:31,881
doctrine applied, then the most detailed map of

115
00:05:32,121 --> 00:05:34,872
your life ever created was available to the

116
00:05:35,111 --> 00:05:37,862
government for the asking.

117
00:05:38,502 --> 00:05:41,232
In 2018, by a vote of five to

118
00:05:41,469 --> 00:05:44,198
four, the Supreme Court ruled for Carpenter.

119
00:05:44,436 --> 00:05:47,165
Accessing his historical location records was a search

120
00:05:47,402 --> 00:05:50,131
under the Fourth Amendment, and to get them,

121
00:05:50,369 --> 00:05:53,098
the government generally needs a warrant.

122
00:05:53,736 --> 00:05:56,524
Chief Justice John Roberts wrote the opinion, and

123
00:05:56,767 --> 00:05:59,555
he was careful about how far it reached

124
00:05:59,797 --> 00:06:02,585
The Court did not throw out the

125
00:06:02,827 --> 00:06:05,615
third-party doctrine. It refused to extend it.

126
00:06:05,858 --> 00:06:08,646
Cell-site location information, Roberts wrote, was a new

127
00:06:08,888 --> 00:06:11,676
kind of record — a comprehensive, detailed, effortless

128
00:06:11,919 --> 00:06:14,707
chronicle of a person's movements, reaching back through

129
00:06:14,949 --> 00:06:17,737
time in a way that no traditional surveillance

130
00:06:17,979 --> 00:06:20,767
ever could.

131
00:06:21,411 --> 00:06:24,423
Two things made it different. First, the depth.

132
00:06:24,685 --> 00:06:27,697
This was not a single trip or a

133
00:06:27,959 --> 00:06:30,971
single call. It was a near-perfect record of

134
00:06:31,233 --> 00:06:34,245
everywhere a person had been for months, revealing

135
00:06:34,507 --> 00:06:37,519
the privacies of life — family, politics, faith,

136
00:06:37,781 --> 00:06:40,793
health — through the simple fact of location

137
00:06:41,055 --> 00:06:44,067
Second, the lack of real choice. You

138
00:06:44,329 --> 00:06:47,341
do not meaningfully volunteer this information. It is

139
00:06:47,603 --> 00:06:50,615
created automatically, just by keeping a phone on

140
00:06:50,877 --> 00:06:53,889
The old idea that you "assumed the

141
00:06:54,151 --> 00:06:57,163
risk" of sharing did not fit a record

142
00:06:57,425 --> 00:07:00,437
you cannot avoid generating.

143
00:07:01,100 --> 00:07:03,480
So the Court drew a line. When the

144
00:07:03,687 --> 00:07:06,067
data is rich enough to map your entire

145
00:07:06,274 --> 00:07:08,655
life, and you have no genuine way to

146
00:07:08,862 --> 00:07:11,242
avoid creating it, sharing it with a company

147
00:07:11,449 --> 00:07:13,829
does not strip away your privacy. The

148
00:07:14,036 --> 00:07:16,416
government still needs a warrant.

149
00:07:17,024 --> 00:07:19,899
The four dissenting justices warned that the Court

150
00:07:20,149 --> 00:07:23,024
had opened a door it could not close

151
00:07:23,274 --> 00:07:26,149
Where exactly is the line? How much

152
00:07:26,399 --> 00:07:29,274
data is too much? Is location special, or

153
00:07:29,524 --> 00:07:32,399
will the same logic eventually cover your emails,

154
00:07:32,649 --> 00:07:35,524
your searches, your purchases? They argued the Court

155
00:07:35,774 --> 00:07:38,649
had traded a clear rule for a vague

156
00:07:38,898 --> 00:07:41,773
one, and that drawing these lines was a

157
00:07:42,023 --> 00:07:44,898
job for legislatures, not judges.

158
00:07:45,549 --> 00:07:48,353
The dissenters had a fair worry. A clear

159
00:07:48,597 --> 00:07:51,401
rule, even an uncomfortable one, tells the police

160
00:07:51,645 --> 00:07:54,449
exactly what they may do. A blurry line

161
00:07:54,693 --> 00:07:57,497
invites years of new cases just to find

162
00:07:57,741 --> 00:08:00,545
where it really falls — and until they

163
00:08:00,789 --> 00:08:03,593
are decided, no one is quite sure.

164
00:08:04,238 --> 00:08:06,586
They were not wrong that the line is

165
00:08:06,790 --> 00:08:09,137
blurry. But the majority had decided that a

166
00:08:09,341 --> 00:08:11,689
blurry line in the right place was better

167
00:08:11,893 --> 00:08:14,241
than a clear rule in the wrong one.

168
00:08:14,846 --> 00:08:17,340
Carpenter is the moment the Fourth Amendment stepped

169
00:08:17,557 --> 00:08:20,051
into the smartphone era. For the first

170
00:08:20,268 --> 00:08:22,763
time, the Court said plainly that digital data

171
00:08:22,980 --> 00:08:25,474
can be so revealing that the old rules

172
00:08:25,691 --> 00:08:28,186
simply do not fit it.

173
00:08:28,803 --> 00:08:31,205
But notice what the decision did not do.

174
00:08:31,414 --> 00:08:33,816
It did not say the government can never

175
00:08:34,025 --> 00:08:36,427
see your data. It said that, for this

176
00:08:36,636 --> 00:08:39,038
kind of record, it usually needs a warrant

177
00:08:39,247 --> 00:08:41,649
— a judge, and probable cause. The

178
00:08:41,858 --> 00:08:44,260
protection is real, and it is also narrow.

179
00:08:44,469 --> 00:08:46,871
The Court deliberately limited the ruling to these

180
00:08:47,080 --> 00:08:49,482
facts and left dozens of harder questions for

181
00:08:49,690 --> 00:08:52,092
later.

182
00:08:52,702 --> 00:08:55,490
And those questions are already here. Your location

183
00:08:55,732 --> 00:08:58,520
is only one of the trails you leave.

184
00:08:58,763 --> 00:09:01,551
There are records of what you search, what

185
00:09:01,793 --> 00:09:04,581
you buy, who you message, and what your

186
00:09:04,824 --> 00:09:07,612
devices sense around you. Each of those is

187
00:09:07,854 --> 00:09:10,642
held by a third party. Each of them,

188
00:09:10,885 --> 00:09:13,673
under the old doctrine, might be fair game.

189
00:09:13,915 --> 00:09:16,703
Carpenter cracked that doctrine open for location data.

190
00:09:16,945 --> 00:09:19,733
It did not resolve the rest.

191
00:09:20,377 --> 00:09:23,409
That is the unfinished part. Carpenter answered the

192
00:09:23,673 --> 00:09:26,705
question for location, but the same logic is

193
00:09:26,969 --> 00:09:30,001
now knocking on every other door — your

194
00:09:30,265 --> 00:09:33,298
searches, your messages, the quiet sensors in the

195
00:09:33,561 --> 00:09:36,594
devices around you. Each new case will ask

196
00:09:36,858 --> 00:09:39,890
the Court to decide, again, whether a record

197
00:09:40,154 --> 00:09:43,186
you cannot avoid creating is still yours.

198
00:09:43,851 --> 00:09:46,288
So the line we started drawing on a

199
00:09:46,500 --> 00:09:48,938
Cleveland sidewalk is still moving. Every new device

200
00:09:49,150 --> 00:09:51,587
asks the same question in a new form:

201
00:09:51,799 --> 00:09:54,237
what have you truly kept private, when modern

202
00:09:54,449 --> 00:09:56,886
life requires you to hand so much of

203
00:09:57,098 --> 00:09:59,535
yourself to someone else just to function?

204
00:10:00,148 --> 00:10:02,507
Three episodes, one question. On a Cleveland sidewalk,

205
00:10:02,712 --> 00:10:05,070
the Court asked how much the police could

206
00:10:05,276 --> 00:10:07,634
do to your body in public. With a

207
00:10:07,839 --> 00:10:10,198
phone seized in an arrest, it asked whether

208
00:10:10,403 --> 00:10:12,762
the device in your pocket was just one

209
00:10:12,967 --> 00:10:15,325
more thing to search. And in Carpenter, it

210
00:10:15,530 --> 00:10:17,889
asked whether a phone that tracks you every

211
00:10:18,094 --> 00:10:20,453
minute could quietly erase everything the first two

212
00:10:20,658 --> 00:10:23,017
cases had built.

213
00:10:23,622 --> 00:10:26,269
The answer, so far, is that the Constitution

214
00:10:26,499 --> 00:10:29,146
is still trying to keep up. The justices

215
00:10:29,376 --> 00:10:32,022
who wrote these rulings could not have imagined

216
00:10:32,253 --> 00:10:34,899
the phone in your pocket. They gave us

217
00:10:35,129 --> 00:10:37,776
tools — reasonable suspicion, reasonable expectation, the warrant

218
00:10:38,006 --> 00:10:40,653
— and left it to each new generation

219
00:10:40,883 --> 00:10:43,529
to decide how those tools apply to machines

220
00:10:43,760 --> 00:10:46,406
that did not exist when the words were

221
00:10:46,636 --> 00:10:49,283
written.

222
00:10:49,914 --> 00:10:52,422
That is the real story under all three

223
00:10:52,640 --> 00:10:55,149
cases. The line between you and the people

224
00:10:55,367 --> 00:10:57,875
who would watch you is not fixed. It

225
00:10:58,094 --> 00:11:00,602
is argued, and redrawn, every time the technology

226
00:11:00,820 --> 00:11:03,329
changes. And right now, that line runs straight

227
00:11:03,547 --> 00:11:06,055
through the device you are probably holding to

228
00:11:06,273 --> 00:11:08,782
watch this.
